<h3>	$B_1$ Inhomogeneity</h3>
	 The $B_1$ field strength represents the strength of the RF coil.
	 The stronger the coils, the higher the $B_1$ value.
	 This value can vary significantly over the imaging volume, with different pixels seeing different $B_1$ strengths.
	 This affects the flip angles (a.k.a. nutation angle; tip angle), which in turn, affects the signal output and yes, the image.
<br/><br/>
Remember from our NMR module that $B_1$ is a rotating magnetic field that
excites the hydrogen proton spins inside a sample and is applied perpendicular to the  $B_0$.
The $B_1$ field is applied in short bursts called RF pulses, causing nutation (tipping).
